<subSubSection pageId="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="20">they can be distinguished by the mostly black pronotal sides.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,893,247,268]" pageId="20">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 
<quantity box="[1004,1093,247,268]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="20" unit="mm" value="3.8">3.8 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[685,762,274,295]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="20" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[771,827,274,295]" pageId="20">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation box="[900,982,274,295]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="24.[175,215,1483,1502]" captionTargetBox="[153,1171,193,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-62@24.[151,1172,192,1460]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figs. 110â€“115. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 110) P. catarina; 111) P. macilentus; 112) P. megalus; 113) P. argus;" pageId="20">Fig. 113</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[992,1109,274,295]" pageId="20">Integument</emphasis>
: Head mostly yellow; epicranium black; antenna mostly brown, capitular antennomeres with yellow makings, apex yellow; pronotal disc mostly black, yellow upper angles, pronotal venter yellow; elytra brown; legs yellow; pterothorax and abdomen brown. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[809,863,433,454]" pageId="20">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes as wide as frons (10:10); funicular antennomeres expanded, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1059,1073,454,468]" fontSize="6" pageId="20">th</superScript>
antennomere not very large (
<figureCitation box="[894,968,486,507]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="17.[197,238,885,904]" captionTargetBox="[189,1161,210,871]" captionTargetId="figure-364@17.[172,1193,183,875]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs. 39â€“47. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 39) P. macilentus; 40) P. megalus; 41) P. argus; 42) P. aspigalbus;" pageId="20">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[987,1062,486,507]" pageId="20">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum quadrate (32:32), lateral tubercle very prominent (
<figureCitation box="[693,770,539,560]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="19.[197,237,1538,1557]" captionTargetBox="[190,1193,191,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-1@19.[172,1193,183,1534]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs. 62â€“75. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 62) P. oxinus; 63) P. alajuela; 64) P. megacavus; 65) P. alboordinus; 66) P. pallidus; 67) P. apolegmus; 68) P. catarina; 69) P. macilentus; 70) P. megalus; 71) P. argus; 72) P. aspigalbus; 73) P. flora; 74) P. posticalis; 75) P. ostrinus." pageId="20">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold gradually diminishing to elytral apex; asetiferous punctures prominent in anterior elytral half. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[910,1010,593,614]" pageId="20">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tegminal lobes and phallic apex as in 
<figureCitation box="[914,988,619,640]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="20.[175,215,1170,1189]" captionTargetBox="[164,629,189,1147]" captionTargetId="figure-461@20.[151,638,183,1159]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs. 76â€“91. Pujoliclerus species, aedeagi. 76) P. helvinus; 77) P. bilineatus; 78) P. calceatus; 79) P. corumba; 80) P. flavolimbatus; 81) P. ovatus (tegmen only); 82) P. wappesi; 83) P. gilvus; 84) P. hermani; 85) P. casselorum; 86) P. catarina (phallus only); 87) P. argus; 88) P. aspigalbus; 89) P. flora; 90) P. posticalis; 91) P. pallidus." pageId="20">Fig. 87</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,810,646,667]" pageId="20">Variation.</emphasis>
The specimens examined are quite homogeneous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,877,699,720]" pageId="20">Natural History.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected during February and October, at 
<quantity box="[1051,1171,725,747]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="20" unit="m" value="225.0" valueMax="250.0" valueMin="200.0">200â€“250 m</quantity>
elevation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,848,778,799]" pageId="20">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[1082,1172,778,799]" name="Ecuador" pageId="20">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[693,782,805,826]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="27.[731,762,861,880]" captionText="Fig. 126. Geographic distribution of seven Pujoliclerus species." pageId="20">Fig. 126</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,824,832,853]" pageId="20">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a Greek adjective that stems from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2014" box="[935,987,858,879]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argus">
<emphasis box="[935,987,858,879]" italics="true" pageId="20">argus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= white). It refers to the pale regions on the capitular antennomeres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
